The standard hot Big-Bang model of cosmology described by a flat ΛCDM universe, with 70% dark energy and 25% cold (non-baryonic) dark matter and 5% baryons (
						Peebles and Ratra, 2003) agrees with cosmological data at large scales (
						Aghanim et al., 2020). There are however a few data-driven problems with the standard ΛCDM paradigm, such as the Hubble constant tension between local and high redshift measurements (
						Shah et al., 2021;
						Di Valentino et al., 2021;
						Verde et al., 2019;
						Bethapudi and Desai, 2017;
						Cervantes-Cota et al., 2023),



									σ


									8


						 tension between galaxy clusters and CMB (
						Abdalla et al., 2022), Lithium-7 problem in Big-Bang nucleosynthesis (
						Fields et al., 2020), etc. An up to date review of all problems and anomalies in ΛCDM can be found in
						Perivolaropoulos and Skara (2022);
						Abdalla et al. (2022);
						Peebles (2022). Therefore a large number of alternate models have been proposed to account for some of these anomalies (
						Bull et al., 2016;
						Banik and Zhao, 2022;
						Abdalla et al., 2022).

Galaxy clusters are the most massive virialized objects in the universe and provide wonderful laboratories for studying a wide range of topics from galaxy evolution to cosmology (
						Vikhlinin et al., 2014;
						Allen et al., 2011;
						Kravtsov and Borgani, 2012) to fundamental Physics (
						Desai, 2018;
						Böhringer and Chon, 2016;
						Bora and Desai, 2021a,b;
						Bora et al., 2022;
						Mendonça et al., 2021). About 10-15% of the mass content comprises of diffuse hot gas in the intracluster medium (ICM). The gas mass fraction defined as the ratio of gas mass to the total mass (



